      "step_index": 4,
      "step_type": "reasoning",
      "content": "## 2) SAR reasoning: why these features matter for CYP2D6 inhibition",
      "tool_name": null,
      "tool_input": null,
      "tool_output": null,
      "timestamp": "2026-02-26T19:43:32.307581+00:00"
    },
    {
      "step_id": "f3c4df1d",
      "step_index": 5,
      "step_type": "reasoning",
      "content": "- **CYP2D6 binding/inhibition commonly depends on ionic interaction** between a **protonated basic N** and an acidic residue in the active site (often described as Asp301 involvement).  \n  \u2192 **Absent here**, so a major binding \u201canchor\u201d is missing.\n- The molecule is **very lipophilic and aromatic**, which can promote **nonspecific P450 binding** in general (hydrophobic active site interactions).  \n  \u2192 Could increase affinity somewhat, but for **CYP2D6 specifically**, lipophilicity alone is usually insufficient for strong inhibition without the basic N.\n- **Phosphate triester** adds polarity and bulk; it can reduce the likelihood of adopting the canonical CYP2D6 inhibitor binding mode and may reduce effective affinity despite lipophilicity.",
      "tool_name": null,
      "tool_input": null,
      "tool_output": null,
      "timestamp": "2026-02-26T19:43:32.307603+00:00"
    },
